<task id="082" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6">
  <metadata>
    <title>D-D-03 Soft Slashes — `/summarize`, `/draft`, `/extract-entities`, `/analyze` (intent shortcuts via agent)</title>
    <phase>Phase D — Command Router + Integration + Closeout</phase>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>6 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>080</dependencies>
    <blocks>084</blocks>
    <tags>frontend, react, ai-widgets, ai, command-router</tags>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Soft slashes route through the agent and influence the LLM's intent classification; touch CapabilityRouter interaction; spec FR-50 binding; Phase D exit criterion 3 binding.</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>D-G1</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>SoftSlashRouter module is isolated; works alongside HardSlashExecutor (081) and ReferenceResolver (083) in disjoint files.</parallel-reason>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Implement the 4 soft-slash commands per spec FR-50 + Q6: `/summarize`, `/draft`,
    `/extract-entities`, `/analyze`. Soft slashes do NOT bypass the LLM — they ROUTE through
    the agent with a prioritized intent signal so existing `CapabilityRouter` matches the
    correct playbook / tool path on first try.

    Build `SoftSlashRouter.ts` alongside `HardSlashExecutor.ts`. When `CommandRouter.parse()`
    returns `isSoftSlash: true`, this router builds a structured intent prefix that the chat
    agent's `CapabilityRouter` recognizes as a strong intent (matching `/summarize` → SUM-CHAT
    playbook directly without natural-language classification).

    Per-command semantics:
    - `/summarize`: route to `invoke_playbook(playbookId: "summarize-document-for-chat@v1")` from
      Pillar 3 + Pillar 4. Agent may ask clarifying questions if no `#<filename>` reference.
    - `/draft`: set draft-intent flag; agent uses draft-mode tool list (existing
      `TextRefinement` + `WorkingDocument` tools from Pillar 2).
    - `/extract-entities`: route to `EntityExtractorHandler` tool from Pillar 2 Wave 2.
    - `/analyze`: set general-analysis-intent flag; agent picks from analysis playbook list.

    The router decorates the message sent to the BFF chat endpoint with a `commandIntent` metadata
    field; CapabilityRouter Layer 1 (existing 3-tier system) reads this and pre-selects.
    No new BFF endpoint. No new tool registration. NFR-11 binding: natural-language equivalents
    still work; soft slashes are explicit shortcuts.

    Frontend-only task; BFF publish-size delta = 0 MB.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior frontend engineer with familiarity with the BFF chat endpoint payload shape +
    CapabilityRouter 3-tier classification. Comfortable with intent prefixing + structured
    message metadata without altering the agent's conversational ability (NFR-01).
  </role>

  <goal>
    Four soft-slash commands work end-to-end. `SoftSlashRouter.ts` decorates the chat message
    payload with a `commandIntent` metadata field that the existing CapabilityRouter Layer 1
    consumes for strong-intent routing. Each soft slash composes correctly with references
    (e.g., `/summarize #file.docx` → invoke_playbook with file reference). Tests verify intent
    prefix is set, agent still conversational (NFR-01), references composable.
  </goal>

